{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565783"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:32:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:32:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18464"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18464"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0,0.63,0.3,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74977"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11193"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60483"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"6576"},{"type":"tags","id":"7903"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30631"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74977"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of dry, itchy, and cracked skin on both hands. She works as a nurse in the intensive care unit and notes the symptoms have worsened since starting this role two months ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has no known allergies and has never experienced similar symptoms before.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are areas of erythema, scaling, and fissuring on the dorsal aspects of both hands, particularly between the fingers. The palms are dry but less affected. There are no vesicles or bullae. No other areas of skin are involved.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Potent topical steroids","Oral antihistamines only","Regular emollients and soap substitutes","Change to non-latex gloves","Cease hand washing between patients"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with irritant contact dermatitis, a common occupational skin condition among healthcare workers. The distribution of the rash and the temporal relationship with increased hand washing and glove use in her new role are typical features. The absence of vesicles and the gradual onset make allergic contact dermatitis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular emollients and soap substitutes\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line management. This helps restore the skin barrier and prevent further damage. Emollients should be applied frequently, particularly after hand washing, and gentle soap substitutes should replace regular soaps which can be irritating.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to non-latex gloves\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying issue, as the dermatitis is more likely due to frequent hand washing and the occlusive effects of gloves rather than latex allergy. If latex allergy was suspected, the presentation would typically include immediate reactions and possibly respiratory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not be effective as this is not primarily a histamine-mediated condition. While antihistamines might help with itching, they do not address the underlying barrier dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotent topical steroids\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as long-term use can lead to skin atrophy and other complications. While a short course of mild to moderate strength topical steroids might be helpful for acute flares, they should not be used continuously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease hand washing between patients\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and unsafe. Hand hygiene is essential for infection control. Instead, the focus should be on using appropriate hand hygiene techniques with gentle products and protecting the skin barrier.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Irritant contact dermatitis commonly affects hands in healthcare workers due to frequent hand washing and glove use.","Management includes avoiding irritants, using soap substitutes, and applying emollients regularly.","Topical steroids are indicated for acute flares of contact dermatitis but should not be used long-term."],"references":["Hand care for healthcare workers. DermNet. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/hand-care-for-healthcare-workers","Nosbaum A, Vocanson M, Rozieres A, Hennino A, Nicolas JF. Irritant and allergic contact dermatitis. Eur J Dermatol. 2009;19(4):325-332 Available at: https://www.john-libbey-eurotext.fr/en/revues/ejd/e-docs/irritant_and_allergic_contact_dermatitis_284156/article.phtml","Flyvholm MA, Bach B, Rose M, Jepsen KF. Self-reported hand eczema in a hospital population. Contact Dermatitis. 2007;57(2):110-115 Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1600-0536.2007.01183.x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60483"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18464"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60483"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T13:09:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T13:10:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11193"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74977"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"